// =============================================================================
// CEL Assertions for SysML v2 Thermal Radiator Model
// Used by Validibot's CEL Assertion Validator (Step 2) to check domain
// constraints that a JSON Schema can't express.
//
// In Validibot, each expression references catalog entry slugs as variables.
// You map data paths from the incoming JSON to named catalog entries (e.g.
// "emissivity" maps to ownedMember[0].ownedAttribute[1].defaultValue), and
// the slug becomes the variable name in the CEL expression.
// =============================================================================


// --- Step 2: Input domain assertions (on the submitted SysML JSON) ----------

// Emissivity must be between 0 (exclusive) and 1 (inclusive).
// Zero emissivity means the surface can't radiate at all.
// Negative emissivity is physically meaningless.
emissivity > 0.0 && emissivity <= 1.0

// Absorptivity must be between 0 and 1 (inclusive).
absorptivity >= 0.0 && absorptivity <= 1.0

// Panel area must be positive.
panelArea > 0.0

// Mass must be positive.
mass > 0.0

// Solar irradiance must be non-negative.
// Zero is valid (eclipse condition). Negative is not.
solarIrradiance >= 0.0

// Every InterfaceDefinition must have exactly 2 ends.
// A thermal coupling with one end doesn't couple anything.
size(end) == 2

// Every SatisfyRequirementUsage must reference a requirement
// that actually exists in the model. Dangling references mean
// your traceability matrix is lying to you.
satisfiedRequirement != null


// --- Step 3: Output assertions (on the FMU simulation results) --------------

// Equilibrium temperature must be within the survivable range
// for spacecraft thermal control coatings (150-400 K).
equilibrium_temp >= 150.0 && equilibrium_temp <= 400.0

// Heat rejected must be positive (a radiator that rejects no heat isn't working).
heat_rejected > 0.0
